  "prompt": "In pregnancy, why is tetracycline contraindicated?",
  "response": "Tetracycline is contraindicated during pregnancy for several important reasons:\n\n1. **Tooth Discoloration and Enamel Hypoplasia**: Tetracycline can affect the development of the fetal teeth. When taken during pregnancy, especially in the second and third trimesters, it can cause permanent yellow, gray, or brown discoloration of the teeth and affect the enamel formation in the developing fetus.\n\n2. **Bone Growth Interference**: Tetracycline can bind to calcium ions in the developing bones of the fetus, potentially inhibiting proper bone growth and causing other skeletal abnormalities.\n\n3. **Hepatic Toxicity**: Pregnant women are at increased risk for liver toxicity when taking tetracycline. This risk is heightened due to the physiological changes during pregnancy that affect liver function.\n\n4. **Potential Teratogenic Effects**: Some studies and clinical observations suggest that tetracycline may have teratogenic effects, though more research is required for definitive conclusions. It is considered prudent to avoid the antibiotic to minimize any potential risk to the fetus.\n\nDue to these risks, healthcare providers generally avoid prescribing tetracycline during pregnancy and opt for safer alternatives when treating infections in pregnant patients.",
